In Week 8, the pattern that had been forming since the start of Trump\'92s second term came into sharp relief. The week did not turn on a single spectacular act, but on a dense run of decisions that pulled more power into the presidency, hollowed out the civil service, and redrew the boundary between citizen and state. Immigration law, trade tools, and executive orders were used less as instruments of policy and more as levers of control. Courts, civil society, and some state officials pushed back in specific cases, but their resistance was fragmentary and reactive. Democracy still functioned, yet the space for independent institutions and equal citizenship narrowed in ways that will be hard to reverse.\
\
At the close of Week 7, the Democracy Clock stood at 8:34 p.m. By the end of Week 8, it had moved to 8:43 p.m., a shift of 8.9 minutes toward midnight. That is a large move for a single week. It reflects not only the volume of events but their structural character. Executive power without effective oversight ticked upward as the White House used orders to dismantle agencies, override courts, and declare emergencies. Law as a weapon, rather than a limit, advanced as immigration statutes and national security language were turned against activists, law firms, and disfavored groups. The civil service became more politicized and privatized under Elon Musk\'92s Department of Government Efficiency, even as judges in California and Maryland ordered thousands of fired workers reinstated. Emergency powers were further normalized, opposition was weakened through budget and staffing cuts, and citizenship itself was stratified by origin and ideology. The clock moved because these shifts were not symbolic flourishes. They changed who holds power, who can contest it, and who counts as fully inside the circle of rights.\
\
The most consequential development of the week was the way immigration law and executive authority were fused into a tool for punishing dissent and redefining belonging. Mahmoud Khalil, a Palestinian activist and recent Columbia graduate with a green card, was arrested by ICE agents at his university housing and moved to detention in Louisiana. His green card had been revoked on a State Department order that cited a rarely used foreign policy provision, claiming his presence could have \'93serious adverse foreign policy consequences.\'94 He was not charged with a crime. His offense, in the government\'92s telling, was activism \'93aligned with Hamas.\'94 The president publicly hailed his arrest as the \'93first of many to come,\'94 and Marco Rubio announced broad plans to revoke visas and green cards of those deemed to support Hamas. Here, immigration law became a blunt instrument against political speech. A lawful resident was treated as an enemy not for what he had done, but for what he represented.\
