Courts intervened, but only at the margins. A federal judge in Manhattan issued an order barring Khalil\'92s deportation pending a hearing, and Judge Jesse Furman in another case ordered that he \'93shall not be removed\'94 until the court decided otherwise. These rulings did not undo the arrest or the weeks in detention, but they drew a line against immediate expulsion. They showed that, for now, judges can still slow the machinery when it is turned against a single person. Yet the administration\'92s broader plans went further. Officials signaled an intent to invoke the Alien Enemies Act, a wartime authority once used to justify Japanese internment, to arrest and deport certain noncitizens without ordinary due process. DHS revoked a Columbia student\'92s visa over alleged Hamas support, leading to self-deportation. A New Hampshire green card holder was reportedly tortured during interrogation at Logan Airport, subjected to violence, sleep deprivation, and denial of medication. These moves together marked a shift from case-by-case enforcement to a regime in which immigration status, nationality, and political views could be grounds for summary treatment.\
