Citizenship itself was redefined from above. On March 14, President Trump ended birthright citizenship by executive action, seeking to prevent children born in the United States to noncitizen parents from obtaining citizenship. This move struck at the core of the 14th Amendment\'92s guarantee and turned a settled constitutional principle into a contested policy preference. The Justice Department, through acting solicitor general Sarah Harris, filed emergency appeals to the Supreme Court to lift injunctions from district courts in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Washington that had blocked the order. The administration argued that universal injunctions hindered the executive\'92s constitutional functions, casting judicial checks as overreach. In parallel, the same week saw the administration\'92s broader immigration crackdown, the suspension of the refugee resettlement program, and the declaration of a national emergency at the southern border. Together, these steps stratified membership in the polity by origin and ideology, with courts struggling to keep pace.\
